		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~markdavis">markdavis</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~markdavis">( 642305 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64535147"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64535147"><p>&gt;"The right of the people to be secure in their persons, houses, papers, and effects, against unreasonable searches and seizures, shall not be violated,"</p><p>In the context of law, generally, a drone observing stuff from the air is considered "in the public", where you have no expectation of privacy.  Even over your own properly.  Observing in public is not a search nor seizure, much less an unreasonable one.</p><p>That said, I don't think such drones should be used over private property without probable cause.   An<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64535147">

